{"type":"message","id":"d25288e5","parentId":"19a89cfa","timestamp":"2026-04-19T16:43:45.629Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_tXV4vjm3vyds96mz1hsLBWwJ","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python tools/list_applications.py","workdir":"/root/.openclaw/workspace","timeout":120,"security":"allowlist"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_bPcoPBdQL0vKmzALYN7RauDa","name":"read","arguments":{"file":"/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/skills/clawflow/SKILL.md"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"ofox-openai","model":"openai/gpt-5.4-mini","usage":{"input":4514,"output":88,"cacheRead":5760,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":10362,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776617023561,"responseId":"chatcmpl-DWPXE1L4wbASjIt918A1NWZTIrqNq"}}
{"type":"message","id":"e2f14d81","parentId":"d25288e5","timestamp":"2026-04-19T16:43:45.726Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_tXV4vjm3vyds96mz1hsLBWwJ","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"status\": \"error\",\n  \"tool\": \"exec\",\n  \"error\": \"exec denied: allowlist miss\"\n}"}],"details":{"status":"error","tool":"exec","error":"exec denied: allowlist miss"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1776617025724}}
{"type":"message","id":"5663ebf4","parentId":"e2f14d81","timestamp":"2026-04-19T16:43:45.739Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_bPcoPBdQL0vKmzALYN7RauDa","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"---\nname: clawflow\ndescription: Use when work should span one or more detached tasks but still behave like one job with a single owner context. ClawFlow is the runtime substrate under authoring layers like Lobster, acpx, or plain code. Keep conditional logic in the caller; use ClawFlow for flow identity, waiting, outputs, and user-facing emergence.\nmetadata: { \"openclaw\": { \"emoji\": \"🪝\" } }\n---\n\n# ClawFlow\n\nUse ClawFlow when a job needs to outlive one prompt or one detached run, but you still want one owner session, one thread context, and one place to inspect or resume the work.\n\n## When to use it\n\n- Multi-step background work with one owner\n- Work that waits on detached ACP or subagent tasks\n- Jobs that may need to emit one clear update back to the owner\n- Jobs that need a small persisted output bag between steps\n\n## What ClawFlow owns\n\n- flow identity\n- owner session and return context\n- waiting state\n- small persisted outputs\n- finish, fail, cancel, and blocked state\n\nIt does **not** own branching or business logic. Put that in Lobster, acpx, or the calling code.\n\n## Runtime pattern\n\n1. `createFlow(...)`\n2. `runTaskInFlow(...)`\n3. `setFlowWaiting(...)` or `setFlowOutput(...)`\n4. `resumeFlow(...)`\n5. `emitFlowUpdate(...)` only when needed\n6. `finishFlow(...)` or `failFlow(...)`\n\n## Example shape\n\n```ts\nconst flow = createFlow({\n  ownerSessionKey,\n  goal: \"triage inbox\",\n});\n\nconst classify = runTaskInFlow({\n  flowId: flow.flowId,\n  runtime: \"acp\",\n  task: \"Classify inbox messages\",\n  currentStep: \"wait_for_classification\",\n});\n\nresumeFlow({\n  flowId: flow.flowId,\n  currentStep: \"route_results\",\n});\n\nsetFlowOutput({\n  flowId: flow.flowId,\n  key: \"classification\",\n  value: { route: \"business\" },\n});\n```\n\n## Keep conditionals above the runtime\n\nUse the flow runtime for state and task linkage. Keep decisions in the authoring layer:\n\n- `business` → post to Slack and wait\n- `personal` → notify the owner now\n- `later` → append to an end-of-day summary bucket\n\n## Examples\n\n- See `skills/clawflow/examples/inbox-triage.lobster`\n- See `skills/clawflow/examples/pr-intake.lobster`\n- See `skills/clawflow-inbox-triage/SKILL.md` for a concrete routing pattern\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1776617025737}}
